10:30.200 --> 10:34.900
So the object literally doesn't exist until you define the forces trying to tear it apart.

10:35.060 --> 10:36.080
You have to start with the destruction.

10:36.080 --> 10:37.960
We start with the destructive forces.

10:38.620 --> 10:42.220
And the thing is just whatever structural pattern refuses to die.

10:42.620 --> 10:44.760
Which leads us to the most practical question, I think.

10:44.900 --> 10:45.360
Which is?

10:45.600 --> 10:48.980
How does anything actually survive this constant bombardment?

10:49.360 --> 10:49.820
Ah.

10:49.820 --> 10:55.220
This is where we leave philosophy and get into the hard mechanics of persistence.

10:56.320 --> 11:02.260
Classical science, especially fundamental physics, has a deep-seated obsession with invariance.

11:02.640 --> 11:06.400
Invariance being things staying exactly mathematically the same.

11:06.780 --> 11:08.240
Like the laws of conservation.

11:08.640 --> 11:09.660
Energy is conserved.

11:09.660 --> 11:10.140
Right.

11:10.480 --> 11:15.860
Another's theorem, conservation of momentum, symmetry, these all rely on invariant properties.

11:16.080 --> 11:17.320
Meaning they don't change at all.

11:17.320 --> 11:22.580
An invariant property is one that a specific transformation leaves completely untouched.

11:23.040 --> 11:26.880
The state before the transformation is absolutely identical to the state after.

11:27.200 --> 11:30.400
And classical thinking treats invariance as the gold standard of reality, right?

11:30.500 --> 11:30.800
It does.

11:30.920 --> 11:33.920
But Flyxion looks at this and points out a devastating limitation.

11:34.620 --> 11:41.160
In the empirical, messy world of biology, human history, and communication, exact invariance is basically a myth.

11:41.320 --> 11:42.080
Because of the noise.

11:42.180 --> 11:42.780
Because of the noise.

11:42.780 --> 11:47.060
If I copy a file on a hard drive enough times, eventually a bit flips.

11:47.320 --> 11:50.360
If a cell divides enough times, a mutation happens.

11:50.460 --> 11:50.820
Exactly.

11:51.140 --> 11:58.180
If persistence required perfect invariance, we would have no biological inheritance, no institutional memory, and no historical records.

11:58.320 --> 12:00.800
The universe would just be empty of complex structures.

12:01.080 --> 12:06.960
So Flyxion introduces a mathematical framework that encompasses invariance but goes much, much further.

12:07.320 --> 12:11.060
It relies on structured domains consisting of four elements.

12:11.180 --> 12:11.960
Let's walk through them.

12:12.120 --> 12:12.580
Let's do it.

12:12.760 --> 12:15.180
First, you have X, the state space.

12:15.180 --> 12:17.660
This is all the possible states your system can be in.

12:17.880 --> 12:18.980
Okay, so X is the arena.

12:19.360 --> 12:23.500
Second, you have T, a family of transformations acting on that space.

12:24.120 --> 12:27.160
The heat, the noise, the passage of time.

12:27.280 --> 12:28.200
The destructive forces.

12:28.520 --> 12:30.780
Third, you have D, a collection of distinctions.

12:31.040 --> 12:35.320
These are the specific differences or structural relationships you actually care about preserving.

12:35.540 --> 12:35.860
Got it.

12:36.080 --> 12:39.260
And fourth, and this is the absolute key to the entire monograph.

12:39.260 --> 12:43.140
You have R, a family of reconstruction operators.

12:43.440 --> 12:44.200
Reconstruction operators.

12:44.380 --> 12:46.440
This is the mechanism that replaces invariance.

12:46.800 --> 12:47.220
It is.

12:47.600 --> 12:56.280
Flyxion states that a distinction persists not if it stays perfectly untouched, but if it can be structurally reconstructed after the transformation has occurred.

12:56.520 --> 12:58.240
Okay, let's ground this in the real world.

12:58.580 --> 13:03.440
Let's look at a mundane, everyday example before we scale back up to ancient caves and DNA.

13:03.600 --> 13:04.100
Sounds good.

